The classic mid-diastolic low-pitched rumbling murmur of mitral stenosis with pre-systolic accentuation is best audible at the apex, in the left lateral position with the bell of the stethoscope. Pre-systolic accentuation usually means the presence of atrial contraction and hence sinus rhythm, but it may persist in AF following short diastoles [6]. The duration of the murmur is directly proportional to the severity of mitral stenosis, but the intensity of the murmur is not. The murmur can be heard provided the atrioventricular gradient remains above 3 mmHg [3]. Because diastolic mean gradient is directly related to heart rate, the manoeuvres that increase heart rate can help to detect an otherwise faint murmur . Source

  • Sound becomes softer when the valves are thickened.
  • volume of S2 depends depends on the severity of pulmonary hypertension.
  • Opening snap: high pitched early diastolic due to sudden tensing of the stiff mitral valve leaflets before opening.
  • Increasing stenosis -> opening snap becomes CLOSER to S2.

  1. In the fasting state, deficiency of insulin conserves glucose and mobilizes stored triglyceride.
    The overall effect of increased triglyceride storage and decreased lipolysis is decreased flux of free fatty acids to the liver. This has indirect but potent action of reducing hepatic gluconeogenesis and hepatic glucose output.
     Under hypoinsulinemic conditions, such as prolonged fasting or uncontrolled diabetes mellitus, fat mobilization is greatly accelerated, resulting in an oversupply of free fatty acids to the liver. In this situation, the liver synthesizes ketone bodies from the abundant supply of acetyl CoA, a by-product of incomplete beta-oxidation of long-chain fatty acids. => [[General medicine 5#DKA pathophysiology|Diabetic ketoacidosis]]
  • Glucagon is ⭐secreted into the portal vein so that there is significant metabolism in the liver before it reaches the systemic circulation. Systemic levels are low.
    Glucagon acts on a GPCR with somewhat organ specific effects.
    • In muscle, glucagon ⭐does not cause glycogenolysis.
    • Exogenous, large doses increases inotropy by increasing myocyte cAMP.
  • ⭐Epinephrine (adrenaline) decreases peripheral uptake of glucose.
    • provides anti-insulin action.
    • This activity is important in type 1 diabetics because they lose the ability to secrete glucagon as well! (protects them against hypoglycaemia)

Basis of macular sparing in occpital lobe infarction:

The tip of the occipital lobe which receives macular retinal signals has dual blood supply from the PCA and MCA. Therefore, occlusion of either one of the arteries will result in macular sparing. Source

[!TIP] Summary: Dysphagia in a ⭐young ⭐man with ⭐history atopy => Eosinophilic oesophagitis

  • ⭐Diagnosis relies on oesophageal biopsy demonstrating eosinophilia.
  • EO is a chronic condition and recurrences will occur.
    Treatment:
  • dietary avoidance of cow's milk and soy products.

Can occur at all ages but rare in childhood.
Pathogenesis: reduction of ganglion cell number in myenteric plexus (Auerbach's plexus). Reduction of ⭐nitric oxide producing neurons; there is loss of inhibitory neurons. There is also reduced production of VIP.

  • gold standard: small bowel biopsy. (Most commonly from duodenum but also from jejunum)
  • Serology is very useful : endomysial (IgA ) and ⭐tissue transglutaminase antibodies.
  • ⭐Combines feature of SLE, Systemic Sclerosis and myositis.
    • Mnemonic: SSP (poly / dermatomyositis)
    • presence of anti-snRNP
    • and dsDNA and anti-Scl70 (SLE and SSc) should be negative.

First pass effect - drug gets metabolized at a non target organ so that effective dose at the target organ is reduced. Commonest site for this to happen is the ⭐liver.

  • P-glycoproteins in the gut can cause efflux of drugs, reducing absorption. Another example of first pass effect.
  • First pass effect is significant only if the liver metabolizes the drug rapidly.
  • So even though the following are completely eliminated by the liver, since the rate of elimination is low, first pass effect is not significant
    More drugs with high FP metabolism:
  1. midazolam,
  2. nifedipine,
  3. propranolol
  4. morphine,
  • First pass metabolism occurs in the gut for 📑 benzylpenicillin (penicillin G) and insulin and
  • in the liver for propranolol, lignocaine, chloromethiasole and GTN.
    | Product may be active | Product is inactive |
    phase 1:
  • Geriatric patients have reduced phase 1 reaction rates.
    Phase 2:
    conjugation: eg: glucuronidation, acetylation and sulfation - make a drug even more soluble by conjugation with another group.
  • Phase 2 reactions result in the formation of readily excreted, less active,nontoxic substances. They are excreted via urine or bile.

Drugs with low intrinsic clearance will have "intrinsic limited" clearance
⭐Drugs with high intrinsic clearance will have "flow limited" clearance.
